POLICE have made a breakthrough in the Melville shooting! SAPS spokeswoman Brigadier Athlenda Mathe said a multi-disciplinary team is working tirelessly on this case to bring to book the perpetrators of this incident in a bid to provide closure to all families involved. She told Daily Sun that the police have recovered nine firearms on a farm in Kliprivier. The firearms were found buried in a shallow grave. “The firearms were taken for ballistics testing and one of the firearms has been positively linked to the shooting that happened during the drive-by shooting in Melville,” said Mathe. You must be SIGNED IN to read comments Police have since been on a manhunt to trace and track down the owner of the farm. “The owner of the farm is known to police and he is urged to hand himself over as the investigation continues,” she said. Mathe also emphasised that the police will not comment further on this matter as this is an ongoing investigation. The story about this tragic incident was published on 1 January 2020. Two women, aged 30 and 40, were killed in a drive-by shooting after an hour South Africa celebrated the arrival of the new year. Six other people were injured in the shooting, two of them were in a critical state and have recovered.